{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"2a7a30df-6549-4d12-99e3-415854ba7e61","content":"Here's what I found:\n\n**`my_app/views.py:3`** — `datetime.now()`\n```python\nnow = datetime.now()\n```\n\nThis is a **hard-coded static call** that makes the function difficult to test because you can't control or predict the returned time.\n\n### Recommended fix: use `django.utils.timezone.now` and inject it\n\n```python\nfrom django.utils import timezone\n\ndef index(request, get_now=timezone.now):\n    now = get_now()\n    return render(request, 'index.html', {'time': now})\n```\n\nThis way, in tests you can pass a lambda or mock:\n\n```python\nfrom datetime import datetime\ndef test_index(rf):\n    fake_now = datetime(2026, 1, 1)\n    response = index(rf.get('/'), get_now=lambda: fake_now)\n```\n\n**Summary:** Only **1 file** with **1 untestable static** found (`datetime.now()`). It also uses naive `datetime` instead of Django's timezone-aware `timezone.now()`, which can cause warnings with `USE_TZ=True`. Want me to apply the fix?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"4b667cf1-8d5f-48bb-9a6d-37d32b8f9217","outputTokens":279,"requestId":"0838:1FFE72:58831E:67B0E5:69EAD458"},"id":"e41a187c-9498-4b13-a7f6-dfcd541438e4","timestamp":"2026-04-24T02:24:34.305Z","parentId":"3d3bdbe1-f91e-4cf9-80c8-bcb75f2a7023"}
